<font color="#FF0000">GENTLEMEN, PART 2 (FINI)</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct 11 20:35:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
One of my co-workers upon learning that I had served in Vietnam became very uncomfortable around me.  I didn't know why until one day she fest up to having gone to protest rallies and being against the war.  She didn't know how I would react or whether we could be friends because of what she did years ago.  She never went out of her way at the time to insult, belittle, or avoid servicepersonnel but she had participated in rallies because she didn't believe Vietnam was a just war. She would have been one of the last people in the world I would have thought would have supported the protest movement.  I know some vets  disagree but I tried to set her at ease.  I don't hold that against her.  <br>
    <br>
I agree each of us has the choice to forgive or not forgive.  What I have observed is that hate has more negative effect on the hator then the hated.  Those who you choose not to forgive don't give a damn or can stand on the morale high ground that they at least tried.  In the mean time you live with that thing eating out your insides.  <br><br>
Anymouse:<br>
I am so confused.  Are you Mustang Two Four, Anonymous?  Pick one name and please, please stick with it.  Anymouse is cute.  <br>
You made my day with the statement that Red Cross workers were ladies because of their deportment not simply because they were female.  When I was a little girl my mother asked what I wanted to be when I grew up.  My response was a &quot;lady&quot;.  Any girl can grow up to be a woman but not all to be ladies. Simple dreams in simpler times. <br><br>
